{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"47f0ea6d-74da-416c-84ee-3e5ccb9ac819","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance **per HTTP request** — each request is a scope. In MAUI, **there are no requests**, so there's no natural scope boundary. `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton`, meaning your `DbContext` lives for the entire app lifetime.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient`** — gives a new `DbContext` per injection:\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddTransient<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n2. **Use `IServiceScopeFactory`** to manually create scopes when you need them:\n   ```csharp\n   using var scope = scopeFactory.CreateScope();\n   var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n3. **Use `IDbContextFactory<T>`** (EF Core recommended pattern for non-request apps):\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n   Then inject and use:\n   ```csharp\n   using var db = dbContextFactory.CreateDbContext();\n   ```\n\nOption 3 is the best practice for MAUI/Blazor/desktop apps — it makes the short-lived nature of each `DbContext` explicit and avoids stale tracking data.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d883482e-ed74-458b-b808-392d2692af72","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common pitfall when migrating from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping, specifically with `AddScoped` and `DbContext`. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly — no tools needed.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request. In MAUI, there's no concept of an HTTP request scope, so `AddScoped` effectively behaves like `AddSingleton` — the same instance lives for the entire app lifetime.","outputTokens":456,"requestId":"0433:1DE8C5:D66C96:F2517D:6A027BFB"},"id":"4e294f9c-e73b-4b4d-912e-02057a5c3d75","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:01:57.818Z","parentId":"9a99e256-5e04-4be9-994f-017804f8